  • With EDA, we also captured with high percentage zero warning and missing values warning occured in dataset.
    • For missing values we should do imputation with linear interpolation.
    • For zero values, I will check whether this zero is from start of the match or it is missinformation, for misinformed values i need to apply also linear interpolation.
      • After checking all distributions and some of the instances there is no misinformation on zero valued instances.
    • Percentage features has close to normal distribution, and seems there are misinformed values because 0 and 100 % are not fitted well on the histogram.
      • Figured that out those are clearly the firts seconds of the match. That is why it is alright to keep it like that.
    • For text features I applied apply one-code encoding to make them binary, to let ML models learn a bit better.
      • Only namefeature of the oppenent teams are not encoded because it is more like the same as fixture_id. If we try to apply league based different models, or add league dimension into dataset, we could apply it on those sophisticated attemps .

missing_features = match_data.columns[match_data.isnull().any()].tolist()

percentage_features = [
    "Successful Passes Percentage - away", 
    "Successful Passes Percentage - home", 
    "Ball Possession % - away", 
    "Ball Possession % - home"
]
text_feature = ["current_state"]

integer_missing_features = set(missing_features) - set(percentage_features + text_feature)

In [89]:
# Imputation for Integer Type Features
for fixture_id, group in match_data.groupby('fixture_id'):
    group = group.sort_values('current_time')

    for feature in integer_missing_features:
        missing_indices = group[group[feature].isna()].index

        for idx in missing_indices:
            valid_before = group.loc[:idx, feature].dropna()
            lower_bound = valid_before.iloc[-1] if not valid_before.empty else pd.NA
            lower_time = group.loc[valid_before.index[-1], 'current_time'] if not valid_before.empty else group.loc[idx, 'current_time']

            valid_after = group.loc[idx:, feature].dropna()
            upper_bound = valid_after.iloc[0] if not valid_after.empty else pd.NA
            upper_time = group.loc[valid_after.index[0], 'current_time'] if not valid_after.empty else group.loc[idx, 'current_time']

            if pd.isna(group.at[idx, feature]):
                if pd.isna(lower_bound) == True & pd.isna(upper_bound) == True:
                    continue
                elif pd.isna(lower_bound):
                    group.at[idx, feature] = 0
                elif pd.isna(upper_bound):
                    group.at[idx, feature] = lower_bound
                else:
                    time_diff = (upper_time - lower_time).total_seconds()
                    value_diff = upper_bound - lower_bound
                    time_diff_missing = (group.loc[idx, 'current_time'] - lower_time).total_seconds()
                    interpolated_value = lower_bound + (value_diff * time_diff_missing / time_diff)
                    group.at[idx, feature] = interpolated_value
        match_data_imputed.loc[group.index, feature] = group[feature]

# Imputation for Float Type Features
for fixture_id, group in match_data.groupby('fixture_id'):
    group = group.sort_values('current_time')

    for feature in percentage_features:
        missing_indices = group[group[feature].isna()].index
        for idx in missing_indices:
            valid_before = group.loc[:idx, feature].dropna()
            lower_bound = valid_before.iloc[-1] if not valid_before.empty else pd.NA
            lower_time = group.loc[valid_before.index[-1], 'current_time'] if not valid_before.empty else group.loc[idx, 'current_time']

            valid_after = group.loc[idx:, feature].dropna()
            upper_bound = valid_after.iloc[0] if not valid_after.empty else pd.NA
            upper_time = group.loc[valid_after.index[0], 'current_time'] if not valid_after.empty else group.loc[idx, 'current_time']

            if pd.isna(group.at[idx, feature]):
                if pd.isna(lower_bound) == True & pd.isna(upper_bound) == True:
                    continue
                elif pd.isna(lower_bound) == True & pd.isna(upper_bound) == True:
                    group.at[idx, feature] = 0
                elif pd.isna(lower_bound) and not pd.isna(upper_bound):
                    group.at[idx, feature] = upper_bound
                elif pd.isna(upper_bound):

                    group.at[idx, feature] = lower_bound
                else:
                    
                    time_diff = (upper_time - lower_time).total_seconds()
                    value_diff = upper_bound - lower_bound
                    time_diff_missing = (group.loc[idx, 'current_time'] - lower_time).total_seconds()
                    interpolated_value = lower_bound + (value_diff * time_diff_missing / time_diff)
                    group.at[idx, feature] = interpolated_value
        match_data_imputed.loc[group.index, feature] = group[feature]
In [92]:
# Imputation for Text Type Features
for fixture_id, group in match_data.groupby('fixture_id'):
    group = group.sort_values('current_time')

    for feature in text_feature:
        missing_indices = group[group[feature].isna()].index
        for idx in missing_indices:
            valid_before = group.loc[:idx, feature].dropna()
            lower_bound = valid_before.iloc[-1] if not valid_before.empty else pd.NA
            lower_time = group.loc[valid_before.index[-1], 'current_time'] if not valid_before.empty else group.loc[idx, 'current_time']

            valid_after = group.loc[idx:, feature].dropna()
            upper_bound = valid_after.iloc[0] if not valid_after.empty else pd.NA
            upper_time = group.loc[valid_after.index[0], 'current_time'] if not valid_after.empty else group.loc[idx, 'current_time']

            if pd.isna(group.at[idx, feature]):
                if pd.isna(lower_bound):
                    group.at[idx, feature] = "X"
                elif pd.isna(upper_bound):
                    group.at[idx, feature] = lower_bound
                else:
                    group.at[idx, feature] = "X"
        match_data_imputed.loc[group.index, feature] = group[feature]

In [101]:
num_bins = 100
match_data_imputed['bin'] = pd.qcut(match_data_imputed['p_home_min_away'], q=num_bins)
match_data_imputed['bin_norm'] = pd.qcut(match_data_imputed['p_home_min_away_norm'], q=num_bins)

bin_stats = match_data_imputed.groupby('bin').agg(
    total_games=('p_tie', 'size'),
    total_draws=('result', lambda x: (x == "X").sum())
)
bin_stats['draw_probability'] = bin_stats['total_draws'] / bin_stats['total_games']

norm_bin_stats = match_data_imputed.groupby('bin_norm').agg(
    total_games=('p_tie_norm', 'size'),
    total_draws=('result', lambda x: (x == "X").sum())
)
norm_bin_stats['draw_probability'] = norm_bin_stats['total_draws'] / norm_bin_stats['total_games']

  • Because filtered a lot of data, need to decrease also bin count to compare both results on the same page.
  • Now the plot is completely changed. When P(Home) - P(Away) value is closer to the 0, market inefficiency clearly can seen on the difference between red dots and blue trend line.
    • While actual probability (historic statistics) are almost close to the 1 when P(Home) - P(Away) difference is close to 0. Market inefficiency can clearly seen here.
    • If correct matches that has high probability of nothing special thing happen choosen, and if P(Home) and P(Away) probabilites are closer to each other, then there is a chance to gain some cash.

Results are completely different after filtering outlier instances, with checking odds bias it can clearly seen.

Task 3¶

Model Structure and Training Strategy¶

  • I choose my decision tree model struce as LightGBM which is one of the boosting tree structure that has some advantages on fast training
  • Models will be trained are multiclass classification with result column target
  • There is two dataset, filtered and imputed
    • If models can't achive enough performance, then we can be do outlier elimination and train our models with filtered dataset.
  • Bookmaker odd probabilties or normalized probabities will be taken and not taken on different trainings because these features could cause leakage
Feature Preparation¶

  • Need to get rid of features that are not needed

    • Time features
      • halftime and minute will be enough for this problem
    • We don't need bookmaker information for this model
    • We can apply team based prediction
      • However, this dataset includes more league than one, it is better to not use team related features and its information in order to avoid high-cardinality
    • bins for task 1 and 2 does not needed here

  • Need to encode these features

    • halftime
    • current_state

#Feature Manipulation for Whole Set
# Delete unnecessary columns
training_data = match_data_imputed.copy()

unnecessary_columns = [
    'fixture_id',
    'current_time',
    'half_start_datetime',
    'match_start_datetime',
    'second',
    'latest_bookmaker_update',
    'name',
    'final_score',
    '1',
    '2',
    'X',
    'bin',
    'bin_norm'
]
training_data.drop(unnecessary_columns, axis='columns', inplace=True)

# One-Hot Encoding
training_data = pd.get_dummies(training_data, columns=["halftime"], prefix = "hf")
training_data = pd.get_dummies(training_data, columns=["current_state"], prefix = "current_state")

# Target Mapping
label_mapping = {"X": 0, "1": 1, "2": 2}
reverse_label_mapping = {v: k for k, v in label_mapping.items()}
training_data['target'] = [label_mapping[label] for label in training_data['result']]
training_data.drop(['result'], axis='columns', inplace=True)


# Features that can cause Leakage (Later dropped from training set)
can_cause_leakage_feats = [
    'p_home_norm',
    'p_away_norm',
    'p_tie_norm',
    'p_home',
    'p_away',
    'p_tie',
    'p_home_min_away',
    'p_home_min_away_norm'
]

    objective = 'multiclass',
    n_jobs = -1,
    random_state = 42,
    metric = "multi_logloss",
    verbose = 0,
    boosting_type='gbdt',

)

)

Model Prediction Probabilities vs Bookmaker Odd Probabilities¶

  • On model 1, bookmaker probabilities are also used as features and they are the top important features as we seen on feature importance table of model 1.

    • This means that while doing prediction of match result, bookmaker probabilities includes important information, but is it inefficient?

  • We will compare model predictions with bookmakers probabilites for each class.

In [238]:
# Calculate Mean Squared Error
mse = np.mean((y_test_pred - y_test_bookmaker) ** 2, axis=1)

# Calculate KL Divergence
kl_divergence = np.sum(y_test_bookmaker * np.log(y_test_bookmaker / (y_test_pred + 1e-10)), axis=1)

# Analyze deviations
deviation_analysis = pd.DataFrame({
    'MSE': mse,
    'KL Divergence': kl_divergence
})

    • Also if we check Kullback-Leibler (KL) Divergence measure used to quantify the difference between two probability distributions. If this divergence value close to 0 then probabilities does not deviate too much. However, when we check the quantiles of KL Divergence values even first quantile it is not close to 0.
